reasoning:
First thing: this is outside my Circle of Competence. I’ve spent my life investing in simple consumer franchises, insurance, banking and utilities—I don’t pretend to understand the inner workings of search algorithms, ad auctions or cloud computing. As I’ve often said, “Risk comes from not knowing what you’re doing,” and with the lack of fundamental, financial or management data here, I simply don’t know this business well enough to make a call.

On moats: Google undoubtedly benefits from network effects and brand strength in search and advertising, but without clear figures I can’t gauge how durable those advantages are against regulatory or competitive threats. Management quality? No insight. Financial health and consistency? No filings, no numbers. Intrinsic value? Can’t compute it when the inputs are missing—rule one of investing is don’t lose money, and I can’t tell if the price leaves any margin of safety.

Long-term prospects in technology can be attractive, but they invite rapid change—something I generally steer clear of except for the rare case like Apple, where the consumer ecosystem creates lasting switching costs. Given the absence of data and my inability to assess valuation or capital allocation, I’d rather put my available capital into businesses I understand: Coca-Cola’s brand, See’s Candies’ pricing power or a solid bank franchise like Bank of America.

When in doubt, I say no. This one earns a neutral signal, not out of dislike for the company, but out of respect for my own limitations and a desire to preserve capital until something better comes along.
